            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-1eaq)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Seinfeld, J. H., & Pandis, S. N. (2006). Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change, 2nd ed. Wiley. Chapter 4 (Atmospheric Radiation and Photochemistry), Eqs. 4.1-4.11, pp. 99-105."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "RadiationFundamentals": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:367\n\nUpstream `RadiationFundamentals` is an MTK `@component` that composes the seven radiation-fundamentals components of Seinfeld & Pandis (2006) Chapter 4 (Eqs. 4.1-4.11) into one system. The upstream constructor is a pure aggregation:\n    @named photon              = PhotonEnergy()\n    @named blackbody           = BlackbodyRadiation()\n    @named wien                = WienDisplacement()\n    @named stefan_boltzmann    = StefanBoltzmann()\n    @named energy_balance      = PlanetaryEnergyBalance()\n    @named climate_sensitivity = ClimateSensitivity()\n    @named toa_forcing         = TOARadiativeForcing()\n    eqs = Equation[]            # No additional equations - all physics is in subsystems\n    return System(eqs, t; systems = [photon, blackbody, wien, stefan_boltzmann,\n                                     energy_balance, climate_sensitivity, toa_forcing], name)\n\nThere are NO connecting equations and NO coupling between the seven subsystems (`eqs = Equation[]`): the upstream model is a structural bag of seven independent components that share only the independent variable t. Each subsystem keeps its own namespace, so e.g. `photon.λ` and `blackbody.λ` are distinct parameters, and `blackbody.T`, `wien.T`, `stefan_boltzmann.T` are three independent temperatures.\n\nMigration shape — `models.RadiationFundamentals` with a `subsystems` block (ESM spec §6.2 / §4.7): the seven components are inlined as named child models under `subsystems`, in the upstream `systems = [...]` order. The top-level model carries no variables and no equations (`\"variables\": {}`, `\"equations\": []`), exactly mirroring the upstream `eqs = Equation[]`. No top-level `coupling` block is emitted because the upstream model has no `couple`/`operator_compose`/`variable_map` connections — the migration-tracker `coupling.couple` feature tag classifies this as a composed `@component`, which the ESS schema represents via `subsystems`, not the `coupling` array (the `coupling` array is for ConnectorSystem equations, of which this model has none).\n\nEach subsystem's `variables` and `equations` are copied verbatim from the corresponding already-migrated standalone `.esm` file in this directory — these are the validated, inline-test-gate-passing migrations of the same seven components:\n  photon              <- components/gaschem/radiation/photon_energy.esm        (PhotonEnergy,        src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:25,  esm-om23)\n  blackbody           <- components/gaschem/radiation/blackbody.esm            (BlackbodyRadiation,  src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:73,  esm-4gsh)\n  wien                <- components/gaschem/radiation/wien.esm                 (WienDisplacement,    src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:121, esm-3e2g)\n  stefan_boltzmann    <- components/gaschem/radiation/stefan_boltzmann.esm     (StefanBoltzmann,     src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:164, esm-mbfz)\n  energy_balance      <- components/gaschem/radiation/planetary_energy_balance.esm (PlanetaryEnergyBalance, src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:211, esm-8b1g)\n  climate_sensitivity <- components/gaschem/radiation/climate_sensitivity.esm  (ClimateSensitivity,  src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:268)\n  toa_forcing         <- components/gaschem/radiation/toa_radiative_forcing.esm (TOARadiativeForcing, src/radiation_fundamentals.jl:327, esm-pbbo)\nInlining (rather than `{\"ref\": \"./photon_energy.esm\"}`) keeps the file fully self-contained per ESM spec §6 (\"All models must be fully specified ... every equation, variable, and parameter must be present in the .esm file\") and avoids the inline-test walker double-processing the referenced standalone files.\n\nStructural fidelity to the upstream tests (GasChem.jl test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl):\n  - `Structural: RadiationFundamentals composed system` (lines 12-28) asserts exactly 7 subsystems named photon/blackbody/wien/stefan_boltzmann/energy_balance/climate_sensitivity/toa_forcing — reproduced here by the 7 keys of the `subsystems` block.\n  - `Analytical: RadiationFundamentals composed system solves` (lines 473-496) asserts the pre-compiled system has `length(equations(radiation)) == 14` (= 2 photon + 1 blackbody + 1 wien + 1 stefan_boltzmann + 3 energy_balance + 4 climate_sensitivity + 2 toa_forcing) and that `radiation.energy_balance.T_e` solves to ~255 K. The migrated file preserves the 14-equation count across the 7 subsystems (stefan_boltzmann contributes its 1 equation as the `observed` variable F_B, which flattens to one algebraic equation) and the `upstream_analytical_composed_solves` test below pins energy_balance.T_e.\n\nenergy_balance subsystem — the upstream `PlanetaryEnergyBalance` is a closed nonlinear system (F_S ~ S_0/4*(1-R_p); F_L ~ sigma*T_e^4; F_S ~ F_L) that MTK solves with a `NonlinearProblem`. The inlined `energy_balance` subsystem carries the closed-form algebraic rewrite from planetary_energy_balance.esm (F_S ~ S_0/4*(1-R_p); T_e ~ (F_S/sigma)^(1/4); F_L ~ sigma*T_e^4) so the Python ESS runner, which integrates a DAE rather than solving a true nonlinear problem, recovers the unique positive-real root without an initial guess. This keeps the 3-equation / 3-state shape of the upstream `length(equations(balance)) == 3` invariant.\n\nParameter overrides on this composed model must be FULLY namespaced (`RadiationFundamentals.<subsystem>.<param>`, e.g. `RadiationFundamentals.energy_balance.R_p`). A bare name (`R_p`) would set every subsystem that has a parameter of that name (R_p exists in both energy_balance and toa_forcing; T in blackbody/wien/stefan_boltzmann; λ in photon/blackbody; S_0 in energy_balance/toa_forcing; F_L in toa_forcing) and a subsystem-relative name (`energy_balance.R_p`) resolves to nothing. Every `parameter_overrides` key in the tests below uses the fully-qualified form; several tests additionally assert that a sibling subsystem's output is UNCHANGED to pin the namespace-isolation contract that the upstream MTK `@named` composition provides.\n\nNo `examples` block: `tools/render_example_plots.py` builds its sweep-resolution plan from a model's own top-level `equations` only and does not recurse into `subsystems`, so it cannot evaluate a pure-aggregation model whose equations all live in child systems. Because RadiationFundamentals has no emergent behavior (zero coupling), every figure it could produce is already produced by the seven standalone subsystem `.esm` files, each of which carries its own `examples` block. Adding a syntactically-present `examples` block here that the renderer can only skip would itself be a migration gap (migration-guide §7.4), so the scientific-figure coverage (§6.2) is delegated to the seven standalone files.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1.0e-9): every one of the 14 equations is algebraic (no time derivative); the ESS runner resolves them by topological substitution into closed form, so each output is correctly-rounded to within a few ULP of the exact real-arithmetic value. rel=1.0e-9 leaves >6 orders of magnitude of headroom above the ~1e-16 ULP floor and matches the looser of the seven standalone subsystem tolerances (blackbody.esm and planetary_energy_balance.esm both use rel=1e-9). Per-assertion `abs=1.0e-12` overrides guard the outputs that are exactly zero by construction (toa_forcing.F_net at radiative equilibrium; climate_sensitivity.ΔF_net / ΔT_e at zero forcing) where a relative tolerance is undefined. The `upstream_analytical_composed_solves` test additionally asserts energy_balance.T_e against the Seinfeld & Pandis book value 255 K at rel=1.0e-2, reproducing the upstream test's `rtol = 1.0e-2` bound.\n\nExpected values were obtained by running the canonical Python ESS runner (`earthsci_toolkit.simulation.simulate`, rtol=1e-10, atol=1e-12, cse=False) — the same path the inline-test gate `tools/run_esm_inline_tests.py` uses — on the flattened composed system, and cross-checked against the pinned values in the seven standalone subsystem `.esm` files (agreement to within last-ULP across all subsystems)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-09
            },
