                "wien": {
                    "variables": {
                        "b": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "m*K",
                            "default": 0.002897,
                            "description": "Wien's displacement constant (S&P Page 100, 4-digit-rounded CODATA). The proportionality between blackbody temperature and peak emission wavelength in λ_max = b/T. The upstream default 2.897e-3 m·K is the historical 4-digit-rounded value; the modern CODATA-2018 value is 2.897771955e-3 m·K which round-trips to 2.898e-3 at four-digit precision (the upstream choice of 2.897 reflects the pre-2014 CODATA value before the latest least-squares adjustment). The constant follows analytically from the transcendental equation x = 5(1-e^(-x)) where x = hc/(kλT) gives x ≈ 4.965114, so b = hc/(k·x) — anchored by the fundamental constants h (Planck), c (speed of light), k_B (Boltzmann)."
                        },
                        "T": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "K",
                            "default": 5800.0,
                            "description": "Temperature of the emitting blackbody (S&P Page 100). The upstream default 5800.0 K is the Sun's effective surface temperature (the temperature of an ideal blackbody emitting the same total radiative flux as the Sun) — sometimes given as 5778 K (the modern IAU 2015 value) but the upstream uses the classic 5800 K round figure. At this temperature, Wien's law gives λ_max = 2.897e-3/5800 = 499.5 nm, the yellow-green visible peak that anchors the human visual system's evolved sensitivity range. Other canonical temperatures: 300 K (Earth surface) → 9.66 μm thermal-IR, 3 K (CMB) → 0.97 mm microwave, 1e6 K (stellar corona/X-ray emission line region) → 2.9 nm soft X-ray."
                        },
                        "λ_max": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "m",
                            "description": "Peak emission wavelength of the blackbody at temperature T (S&P Eq. 4.3). λ_max is the wavelength at which the Planck spectral function dF_Bλ/dλ = 0 — the maximum of the spectral emission curve. The temperature-inverse scaling λ_max ∝ 1/T means hotter sources emit at shorter wavelengths: the canonical fact behind the visible spectrum of stars (red giants vs blue dwarfs), the color of a heated metal as it warms from red-hot to white-hot, and the separation of solar (shortwave) from terrestrial (longwave) radiation that anchors the planetary energy balance in S&P Chapter 4. The peak wavelength is one of three derived quantities from the Planck function (peak λ_max from Wien, total flux F_B from Stefan-Boltzmann, spectral shape F_Bλ from Planck itself) that together characterize blackbody emission."
                        }
                    },
                    "equations": [
