                "energy_balance": {
                    "variables": {
                        "sigma": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/(m^2*K^4)",
                            "default": 5.671e-08,
                            "description": "Stefan-Boltzmann constant (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Eq. 4.4 / Ch. 4 §4.1) — upstream `@constants` sigma; the proportionality constant in the Stefan-Boltzmann law for emissive power of a blackbody. Default 5.671e-8 W/(m^2*K^4) matches the upstream Julia source verbatim; CODATA 2018 value is 5.670374419e-8 W/(m^2*K^4), within ~1e-4 relative of the upstream rounded value."
                        },
                        "S_0": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 1370.0,
                            "description": "Solar constant — total radiative flux per unit area at the top of Earth's atmosphere measured normal to the Sun's direction at 1 AU. Default 1370 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source and Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 p. 101; modern observation-derived total solar irradiance is ~1361 W/m^2 (Kopp & Lean 2011). The factor of 4 in Eq. 4.5 (`S_0/4 * (1 - R_p)`) is the ratio of Earth's geometric cross-section (pi*R^2) to its surface area (4*pi*R^2) — averages the per-area solar flux from the cross-section that intercepts the beam onto the full surface area."
                        },
                        "R_p": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 0.3,
                            "description": "Planetary albedo (dimensionless) — fraction of incident solar radiation reflected back to space by clouds, atmosphere, and surface. Default 0.3 matches the upstream Julia source and Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 p. 101 (the standard Earth-with-clouds value). The same upstream test family exercises R_p = 0.15 (Earth without clouds, T_e ~ 268 K), R_p = 0 (perfect absorber, T_e ~ 278.77 K), and R_p = 0.99 (near-perfect reflector, T_e ~ 88.16 K)."
                        },
                        "F_S": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 240.0,
                            "description": "Absorbed solar flux at the top of atmosphere averaged over Earth's surface (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.5): F_S = S_0/4 * (1 - R_p). Default initial value 240 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source `F_S(t) = 240.0` — the convergence target near 239.75 W/m^2 at the canonical defaults (S_0 = 1370, R_p = 0.3). At equilibrium F_S = F_L (Eq. 4.7)."
                        },
                        "F_L": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 240.0,
                            "description": "Emitted longwave (terrestrial) radiative flux at the top of atmosphere (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.6, Stefan-Boltzmann law): F_L = sigma * T_e^4. Default initial value 240 W/m^2 matches the upstream Julia source `F_L(t) = 240.0`. At equilibrium F_L = F_S (Eq. 4.7); the migrated algebraic chain enforces this by composition through T_e."
                        },
                        "T_e": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "K",
                            "default": 255.0,
                            "description": "Planetary equilibrium temperature (Seinfeld & Pandis Eq. 4.7): the temperature at which the emitted longwave flux F_L = sigma * T_e^4 balances the absorbed solar flux F_S = S_0/4 * (1 - R_p). Closed-form: T_e = (S_0/4 * (1 - R_p) / sigma)^(1/4). Default initial value 255 K matches the upstream Julia source `T_e(t) = 255.0` — the convergence target at the canonical defaults (S_0 = 1370, R_p = 0.3); upstream Julia `NonlinearProblem` uses 250 K as the initial guess and converges to ~254.99 K (book value 255 K)."
                        }
                    },
                    "equations": [
                        {
                            "lhs": "F_S",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "S_0",
                                            4.0
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [
                                            1.0,
                                            "R_p"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "T_e",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "F_S",
                                            "sigma"
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    0.25
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "F_L",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "sigma",
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            "T_e",
                                            4.0
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                "climate_sensitivity": {
                    "variables": {
                        "σ": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/(m^2*K^4)",
                            "default": 5.671e-08,
                            "description": "Stefan-Boltzmann constant (S&P Page 101). The proportionality between blackbody temperature and total emitted radiative power per unit area. The upstream default 5.671e-8 W/(m^2·K^4) is the CODATA value rounded to four significant figures (the modern CODATA-2018 value is 5.670374...e-8, which round-trips to 5.671e-8 at four-digit precision)."
                        },
                        "T_e": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "K",
                            "default": 255.0,
                            "description": "Reference equilibrium temperature for the climate-sensitivity expansion (S&P Page 104). 255 K is Earth's no-greenhouse effective radiating temperature — the temperature a perfect blackbody planet receiving Earth's net solar flux F_S = (1-R_p)·S_0/4 ≈ 240 W/m^2 would have. The actual Earth's surface temperature (~288 K) exceeds T_e by the greenhouse-effect warming of ~33 K. Climate-sensitivity diagnostics are conventionally evaluated at T_e (the planetary radiative balance temperature) rather than at the surface — F_L = σ·T_e^4 must match F_S at radiative equilibrium."
                        },
                        "ΔF_S": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 4.0,
                            "description": "Perturbation to the absorbed solar flux (S&P Eq. 4.8). Positive ΔF_S means more solar energy absorbed (e.g., reduced cloud albedo, reduced ice cover, increased solar luminosity). The upstream default 4.0 W/m^2 is a representative CO2-doubling-equivalent forcing — close to but slightly smaller than the often-cited 4.6 W/m^2 CO2-doubling estimate the upstream test uses for the secondary canonical case."
                        },
                        "ΔF_L": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 0.0,
                            "description": "Perturbation to the emitted longwave flux (S&P Eq. 4.8). Positive ΔF_L means more longwave radiation escaping to space (e.g., reduced opacity of the atmosphere). The default ΔF_L = 0.0 places the full forcing on the solar side, isolating the temperature response to a pure ΔF_S perturbation."
                        },
                        "ΔF_net": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "description": "Net radiative-forcing perturbation, ΔF_net = ΔF_S - ΔF_L (S&P Eq. 4.8). Positive ΔF_net means the planet receives more net incoming energy than the reference state and must warm to restore balance. This is the input to the linear climate-sensitivity relation ΔT_e = λ_0·ΔF_net."
                        },
                        "ΔT_e": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "K",
                            "description": "Change in equilibrium temperature responding to the net radiative forcing (S&P Eq. 4.9). ΔT_e = λ_0·ΔF_net is the linear-response approximation of the (small-perturbation) temperature change. At Earth's T_e = 255 K, λ_0 ≈ 0.27 K·m^2/W, so a 4 W/m^2 forcing (≈ CO2 doubling) gives ΔT_e ≈ 1.06 K — the no-feedback Planck response, against which feedback-amplified ΔT_e estimates (~1.5-4.5 K for CO2 doubling per IPCC) are conventionally reported."
                        },
                        "λ_0": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "K*m^2/W",
                            "description": "Climate-sensitivity factor in the no-feedback (Planck) limit (S&P Eq. 4.10). λ_0 = 1 / (4·σ·T_e^3) is the analytic inverse of dF_L/dT_e at the reference state — the temperature change per unit radiative forcing that holds when no feedbacks amplify or damp the response. Equivalently λ_0 = T_e / (4·F_L), where F_L is the reference longwave flux. At Earth's T_e = 255 K, λ_0 ≈ 0.27 K·m^2/W; a 1 K cooler T_e would raise λ_0 by ~1% (∂λ_0/∂T_e = -3·λ_0/T_e). The factor is the baseline against which feedback-amplified sensitivities are reported — IPCC equilibrium climate sensitivity ECS = λ·ΔF_2xCO2 where λ ≈ 2-6 × λ_0 captures water vapor, lapse rate, albedo, and cloud feedbacks."
                        },
                        "F_L": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "description": "Reference longwave flux at the reference temperature, F_L = σ·T_e^4 (Stefan-Boltzmann law applied at T_e). At Earth's T_e = 255 K, F_L ≈ 239.78 W/m^2 — matches (within rounding) the absorbed solar flux F_S ≈ 239.75 W/m^2 (S&P p. 101: F_S = (1-R_p)·S_0/4 at R_p=0.3, S_0=1370 W/m^2). Exposed as a state variable so the alternative form λ_0 = T_e / (4·F_L) can be verified directly against λ_0 = 1 / (4·σ·T_e^3) — they are algebraically identical (multiply numerator and denominator of the second form by T_e to get the first)."
                        }
                    },
                    "equations": [
                        {
                            "lhs": "ΔF_net",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    "ΔF_S",
                                    "ΔF_L"
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "λ_0",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "/",
                                "args": [
                                    1,
                                    {
                                        "op": "*",
                                        "args": [
                                            4,
                                            "σ",
                                            {
                                                "op": "^",
                                                "args": [
                                                    "T_e",
                                                    3
                                                ]
                                            }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "ΔT_e",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "λ_0",
                                    "ΔF_net"
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "F_L",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    "σ",
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            "T_e",
                                            4
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                "toa_forcing": {
                    "variables": {
                        "S_0": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 1370.0,
                            "description": "Solar constant — the time-averaged solar irradiance at the top of Earth's atmosphere measured perpendicular to the Sun-Earth line (Seinfeld & Pandis 2006 Page 100, IPCC TAR canonical value). Modern accepted value from CODATA / TIM satellite measurements is ~1361 W/m²; the upstream uses the round 1370 W/m² for textbook consistency. Drives the absorbed solar flux F_S via the planetary-cross-section factor 1/4."
                        },
                        "R_p": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "1",
                            "default": 0.3,
                            "description": "Planetary albedo (dimensionless) — the fraction of incoming solar flux reflected back to space by clouds (~2/3), ice/snow, ocean, and land surfaces. Default 0.3 is Earth's Bond albedo including clouds (S&P Page 101). Removing clouds gives R_p ≈ 0.15 (T_e ≈ 268 K, S&P Page 102); the no-cloud / no-ice limit gives R_p ≈ 0.07 (just ocean / land surface reflection); the all-ice snowball-Earth limit gives R_p ≈ 0.6+ (T_e ≈ 220 K). The (1-R_p) factor in F_S is the fraction of incoming solar absorbed by the planet."
                        },
                        "F_L": {
                            "type": "parameter",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "default": 239.75,
                            "description": "Emitted longwave flux at TOA (W/m²) — the outgoing thermal radiation the planet emits, treated here as an input parameter. Default 239.75 W/m² is chosen to exactly balance F_S at the default solar constant and albedo (radiative equilibrium F_net = 0). In a coupled system, F_L would be computed by the sibling StefanBoltzmann component as σT_e^4 with T_e ≈ 255 K (5.671e-8 · 255^4 ≈ 239.75 W/m²). A consumer studying a forcing scenario can override F_L: e.g. doubling CO₂ raises F_L by ~4-5 W/m² instantaneously before the surface temperature responds (S&P Page 105 quotes 4.6 W/m² for CO₂ doubling), producing a transient negative F_net ≈ -4 W/m² that drives subsequent warming."
                        },
                        "F_net": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "description": "Net radiative flux at TOA (W/m²) — F_net = F_S - F_L. Positive: planet gaining energy (warming). Negative: planet losing energy (cooling). At Earth's default radiative-balance parameters F_net = 0 exactly. The IPCC AR6 estimate of the present-day Earth-system energy imbalance is +0.79 W/m² (2006-2018, Forster et al. 2021), consistent with ongoing greenhouse-driven warming."
                        },
                        "F_S": {
                            "type": "state",
                            "units": "W/m^2",
                            "description": "Absorbed solar flux at TOA (W/m²) — F_S = S_0/4 · (1 - R_p). The factor 1/4 is the planetary geometric correction (planet intercepts solar flux over πR² but emits over 4πR²); the factor (1 - R_p) is the fraction of incoming solar absorbed (1 minus reflected). At Earth's defaults: F_S = 1370/4 · 0.7 = 239.75 W/m²."
                        }
                    },
                    "equations": [
                        {
                            "lhs": "F_S",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "S_0",
                                            4.0
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    {
                                        "op": "-",
                                        "args": [
                                            1.0,
                                            "R_p"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "lhs": "F_net",
                            "rhs": {
                                "op": "-",
                                "args": [
                                    "F_S",
                                    "F_L"
                                ]
                            }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            },
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "composed_default_canonical_all_subsystems",
                    "description": "Canonical default-parameter run of the composed system. Reproduces the intent of the upstream `Structural: RadiationFundamentals composed system` test (test/radiation_fundamentals_test.jl:12-28, which asserts the 7 named subsystems photon/blackbody/wien/stefan_boltzmann/energy_balance/climate_sensitivity/toa_forcing) by exercising one canonical output of every one of the 7 subsystems through the dot-namespaced flattened system: photon at the 500 nm visible-green default (ν, Δε), blackbody at T=5800 K / λ=500 nm (F_B_λ), wien at T=5800 K (λ_max), stefan_boltzmann at T=255 K (F_B), energy_balance at S_0=1370 / R_p=0.3 (F_S, T_e, F_L), climate_sensitivity at ΔF_S=4.0 (ΔF_net, λ_0, ΔT_e, F_L), toa_forcing at the radiative-equilibrium defaults (F_S, F_net≈0). Every value is cross-checked against the pinned values in the standalone subsystem .esm files (agreement to last-ULP).",
